ğŸ”¸ What is HTTP?

HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol) is a protocol used to transfer data between a client (browser/ app) and a server.

Works on port 80

Unsecured â†’ data is sent as plain text

Anyone intercepting the traffic can read/modify it

Used for general browsing (not recommended today)

ğŸ”¹ What is HTTPS?

HTTPS (HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure) is the secure version of HTTP.

Works on port 443

Uses SSL/TLS encryption to protect data

Ensures:

ğŸ”’ Confidentiality

âœ” Integrity

ğŸ›‚ Authentication

Mandatory for websites, APIs, banking, login pages

ğŸ” Key Differences: HTTP vs HTTPS
Feature	HTTP	HTTPS
Security	Not secure	Encrypted & secure
Data Transfer	Plain text	Encrypted with SSL/TLS
Port	80	443
URL Prefix	http://	https://
Certificate	No certificate required	Requires SSL/TLS certificate
SEO	Lower ranking	Better ranking (Google prefers HTTPS)
Performance	Slightly faster (older days)	HTTP/2 & HTTP/3 make HTTPS faster now
Use Cases	Non-sensitive browsing	Secure websites, APIs, payments
ğŸ” Why HTTPS Is More Secure

HTTPS uses SSL/TLS to provide:

âœ” 1. Encryption

Even if someone captures traffic, they cannot read it.

âœ” 2. Authentication

Confirms you're communicating with the real server.

âœ” 3. Data Integrity

Data cannot be modified during transmission.

ğŸš€ Which One Should You Use?

Always HTTPS.
Modern browsers label HTTP sites as "Not Secure".

APIs, e-commerce, banking, login systems â†’ must use HTTPS.

ğŸ¯ Summary

HTTP = simple, fast, but unsecured

HTTPS = secure, encrypted, trusted

HTTPS protects users and helps with SEO and credibility